dataset.abstract: Under the Biodiversity Conservation Initiative of the Science Division of the Department of Parks and Wildlife, Western Australia, Western Australia funding was provided for a floristic survey of the Ravensthorpe Range. Phase 1 of this survey involved the establishment of 200 permanent quadrats covering the geomorphologic, geologic and floristic variation across the range. The data resulting from Phase 1 of the the survey is intended to more fully document the conservation values of the range and provide a regional context to assess any proposed developments. Phase 1 of this survey was undertaken by the consulting firm Western Botanical (http://www.westernbotanical.com.au/). Phase 2 of this survey involved the establishment of a further 66 permanent quadrats and a detailed analysis of the compositional vegetation patterns across the range based on all 266 quadrats. Phase 2 field observation and analysis was undertaked by DPaW Science Division staff. Phase 2 of the Ravensthorpe Range Survey is not currently published in TERN ÆKOS. Please use the following URL to access the dataset: http://aekos.org.au/collection/wa.gov.au/ravensthorpe

methodStep.description: Title, purpose and summary of each individual method Plot Establishment Method: Broad study locations were selected prior to visiting the study area based on sampling a representative range of locations across the different geological units of the Ravensthorpe Range. Final location of the sampling plots was selected in the field based on access considerations. 200 plots were established across the Ravensthorpe Range between February and October 2007 (see Figure 1 for distribution of plots). Plot establishment and configuration follows that used in the WA Department of Parks and Wildlife regional wheatbelt survey (Gibson et al. 2004). ; Vegetation Assessment Method: Over half (119) of the Phase 1 plots were established and surveyed for landscape features, soil properties and vegetation diversity between February and May of 2007 and then re-surveyed for vegetation species during the spring survey period with only additional observed species recorded (i.e. species not observed in the autumn survey period). The remaining 81 Phase 1 plots were established and surveyed for landscape features, soil properties and vegetation diversity during the spring 2007 survey period. The vegetation of each plot was described in terms of its overall structure, species diversity and species cover, phenology and life-form. Field identifications were verified by the systematic collection of voucher specimens which were lodged with the Western Australian Herbarium. ; Surface Soil Assessment Method: Field soil texture and soil surface description followed McDonald and Isbell (1990), and Munsell (1994) soil colour charts were used to measure soil colour. 20 samples of surface soil are collected from the top 10cm of soil at 20 points across the understorey plot. These samples are combined and passed through a 2mm sieve to remove coarse fragments and then sampled for a wide range of soil chemistry parameters in a laboratory environment. ; Surface Cover AssessmentMethod: Standard cover categories from McDonald, Isbell and Speight (1990) are used to categorize the proportional cover of leaf litter and bare ground across the understorey plot. ; Landscape Assessment Method: Landscape assessment describes a range of physical (abiotic) features of the plot and its surrounding landscape. Except for general the location description, landform pattern and landform element values, all landscape and physical features are measured at the understorey plot scale. Landscape features are not likely to change between visits and as such are only recorded once during the first visit to the plot. Landscape feature assessment is based on standard methods as described in McDonald, Isbell and Speight (1990). ; Disturbance Assessment Method: The observer assesses the degree and type of anthropogenic disturbance across the understorey plot and selects the category which best describes it. Disturbance categories are based on McDonald, Isbell and Speight (1990).
